### Plotting Lyapunov Exponent vs. r

Let's compute `λ(r)` over a range and plot it. Positive regions are chaotic; negative regions are stable.

```scheme
(define (lyapunov f df x0 n)
  (let loop ((x x0) (sum 0) (i 0))
    (if (>= i n)
        (/ sum n)
        (let ((deriv-val (df x)))
          (loop (f x)
                (+ sum (math/log (abs deriv-val)))
                (+ i 1))))))

(define (logistic r)
  (lambda (x) (* r x (- 1 x))))

(define (logistic-deriv r)
  (lambda (x) (* r (- 1 (* 2 x)))))

(define (lyapunov-spectrum r-min r-max r-step)
  (let r-loop ((r r-min))
    (if (> r r-max)
        '()
        (let ((lam (lyapunov (logistic r) (logistic-deriv r) 0.4 500)))
          (cons (list r lam)
                (r-loop (+ r r-step)))))))

(define spectrum (lyapunov-spectrum 2.5 4.0 0.01))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/line spectrum))
```

[VISUAL: A line plot with r on horizontal axis, λ on vertical. Negative until r~3, drops at bifurcations, crosses zero into positive (chaos), dips back negative at windows of order.]

<!-- BUILD: run; Lyapunov spectrum -->

The crossings from negative to positive mark the **onset of chaos**. The dips back down are periodic windows.

