## §3. Two-Dimensional Systems and Phase Portraits

So far we've studied one variable evolving. Real-world systems often have multiple interacting variables. A **two-dimensional dynamical system** has the form:

```
x(n+1) = f(x(n), y(n))
y(n+1) = g(x(n), y(n))
```

The pair `(x, y)` is called the **state**. The **phase portrait** plots trajectories in the `(x, y)` plane.

**Examples:** predator-prey (foxes and rabbits), competing species, pendulum position and velocity, chemical concentrations.

We'll focus on **continuous-time** systems (differential equations) approximated by discrete steps.

---

### The Harmonic Oscillator

The simplest 2D system is the **harmonic oscillator** (a spring):

```
dx/dt = v
dv/dt = -x
```

Here `x` is position, `v` is velocity. It's Newton's second law `F = ma` with `F = -x` (Hooke's law) and `m = 1`.

We approximate the continuous system with small time steps (Euler's method):

```
x_new = x + v·Δt
v_new = v - x·Δt
```

Let's iterate it.

```scheme
(define (harmonic-step x v dt)
  ;; Returns (list x_new v_new)
  (let ((x-new (+ x (* v dt)))
        (v-new (- v (* x dt))))
    (list x-new v-new)))

(define (orbit-2d step state0 dt n)
  ;; step is a function (x v) -> (x' v')
  ;; Returns list of states
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (step (car state0) (cadr state0) dt)))
        (cons state0 (orbit-2d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(orbit-2d harmonic-step (list 1 0) 0.1 20)
```

[VISUAL: A list of (x v) pairs.]

<!-- BUILD: run; print first 20 states -->

Let's plot the trajectory in the `(x, v)` plane.

```scheme
(define (harmonic-step x v dt)
  (let ((x-new (+ x (* v dt)))
        (v-new (- v (* x dt))))
    (list x-new v-new)))

(define (orbit-2d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (step (car state0) (cadr state0) dt)))
        (cons state0 (orbit-2d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define traj (orbit-2d harmonic-step (list 1 0) 0.05 200))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/line traj))
```

[VISUAL: A closed loop (ellipse) in the (x, v) plane — the orbit is periodic.]

<!-- BUILD: run; phase portrait shows ellipse -->

The harmonic oscillator's orbits are **closed curves**. The system oscillates forever.

---

### Multiple Trajectories: A Phase Portrait

Let's plot several orbits starting from different initial conditions.

```scheme
(define (harmonic-step x v dt)
  (let ((x-new (+ x (* v dt)))
        (v-new (- v (* x dt))))
    (list x-new v-new)))

(define (orbit-2d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (step (car state0) (cadr state0) dt)))
        (cons state0 (orbit-2d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define (make-trajectories initials)
  (map (lambda (ic)
         (orbit-2d harmonic-step ic 0.05 150))
       initials))

(define initials (list (list 0.5 0) (list 1 0) (list 1.5 0)
                       (list 0 0.5) (list 0 1)))

(define trajs (make-trajectories initials))

(plot/render-svg
  (apply plot/with
         (map plot/line trajs)))
```

[VISUAL: A phase portrait with concentric ellipses around the origin. Each initial condition traces its own closed orbit.]

<!-- BUILD: run; multiple ellipses -->

The **fixed point** at `(0, 0)` is called a **center**: orbits circle it forever, neither converging nor diverging.

---

### A Damped Oscillator (Spiral Sink)

Add damping: `dv/dt = -x - 0.2v`. Energy dissipates; orbits spiral inward.

```scheme
(define (damped-step x v dt)
  (let ((x-new (+ x (* v dt)))
        (v-new (- v (* (+ x (* 0.2 v)) dt))))
    (list x-new v-new)))

(define (orbit-2d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (step (car state0) (cadr state0) dt)))
        (cons state0 (orbit-2d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define traj (orbit-2d damped-step (list 2 0) 0.05 300))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/line traj))
```

[VISUAL: A spiral converging to the origin.]

<!-- BUILD: run; inward spiral -->

The origin is now a **stable spiral** (or **spiral sink**). All orbits converge to it.

---

### An Unstable Spiral (Spiral Source)

Flip the damping sign: `dv/dt = -x + 0.1v`. Orbits spiral **outward**.

```scheme
(define (unstable-step x v dt)
  (let ((x-new (+ x (* v dt)))
        (v-new (+ v (* (- (* 0.1 v) x) dt))))
    (list x-new v-new)))

(define (orbit-2d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (step (car state0) (cadr state0) dt)))
        (cons state0 (orbit-2d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define traj (orbit-2d unstable-step (list 0.1 0.1) 0.05 150))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/line traj))
```

[VISUAL: A spiral expanding from the origin.]

<!-- BUILD: run; outward spiral -->

The origin is a **spiral source**. Nearby orbits diverge.

---

### A Saddle Point

Consider `dx/dt = x`, `dv/dt = -v`. The x-direction grows exponentially; v decays.

```scheme
(define (saddle-step x v dt)
  (let ((x-new (+ x (* x dt)))
        (v-new (- v (* v dt))))
    (list x-new v-new)))

(define (orbit-2d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (step (car state0) (cadr state0) dt)))
        (cons state0 (orbit-2d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define traj1 (orbit-2d saddle-step (list 0.1 0.5) 0.05 80))
(define traj2 (orbit-2d saddle-step (list 0.5 0.1) 0.05 80))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/with
    (plot/line traj1)
    (plot/line traj2)))
```

[VISUAL: One trajectory expands along the x-axis, the other contracts along the v-axis. The origin is a saddle.]

<!-- BUILD: run; saddle structure -->

A **saddle point** is unstable: orbits are attracted in one direction and repelled in another.

---

### The Pendulum (Nonlinear System)

A pendulum's equation is `dθ/dt = ω`, `dω/dt = -sin(θ)`. Unlike the linear oscillator, this is **nonlinear** (because of `sin`).

```scheme
(define (pendulum-step theta omega dt)
  (let ((theta-new (+ theta (* omega dt)))
        (omega-new (- omega (* (sin theta) dt))))
    (list theta-new omega-new)))

(define (orbit-2d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (step (car state0) (cadr state0) dt)))
        (cons state0 (orbit-2d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define traj (orbit-2d pendulum-step (list 0.5 0) 0.05 300))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/line traj))
```

[VISUAL: An ellipse-like closed orbit in (θ, ω) space — small oscillations.]

<!-- BUILD: run; small-amplitude pendulum orbit -->

For small angles, `sin(θ) ≈ θ`, so the pendulum behaves like a harmonic oscillator. But for large angles:

```scheme
(define (pendulum-step theta omega dt)
  (let ((theta-new (+ theta (* omega dt)))
        (omega-new (- omega (* (sin theta) dt))))
    (list theta-new omega-new)))

(define (orbit-2d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (step (car state0) (cadr state0) dt)))
        (cons state0 (orbit-2d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define traj-large (orbit-2d pendulum-step (list 2.5 0) 0.05 500))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/line traj-large))
```

[VISUAL: A larger, more squashed orbit — nonlinear distortion visible.]

<!-- BUILD: run; large-amplitude orbit -->

The phase portrait changes shape. Nonlinearity matters.

