### Predator-Prey: The Lotka-Volterra Model

A classic ecological model:

```
dx/dt = a·x - b·x·y   (prey grow, eaten by predators)
dy/dt = c·x·y - d·y   (predators need prey, die otherwise)
```

Let `a=1, b=0.1, c=0.075, d=0.5`.

```scheme
(define (lotka-step x y dt)
  ;; x = prey, y = predator
  (let ((a 1) (b 0.1) (c 0.075) (d 0.5))
    (let ((dx (* (- (* a x) (* b x y)) dt))
          (dy (* (- (* c x y) (* d y)) dt)))
      (list (+ x dx) (+ y dy)))))

(define (orbit-2d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (step (car state0) (cadr state0) dt)))
        (cons state0 (orbit-2d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define traj (orbit-2d lotka-step (list 10 5) 0.1 500))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/line traj))
```

[VISUAL: A closed loop in (x, y) space — populations oscillate.]

<!-- BUILD: run; predator-prey cycle -->

Prey increase → predators increase (more food) → prey decrease (overhunting) → predators decrease (starvation) → prey recover → cycle repeats. The orbit is a **limit cycle**.

---

### Time Series of Predator and Prey

Let's plot populations over time.

```scheme
(define (lotka-step x y dt)
  (let ((a 1) (b 0.1) (c 0.075) (d 0.5))
    (let ((dx (* (- (* a x) (* b x y)) dt))
          (dy (* (- (* c x y) (* d y)) dt)))
      (list (+ x dx) (+ y dy)))))

(define (orbit-2d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (step (car state0) (cadr state0) dt)))
        (cons state0 (orbit-2d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define traj (orbit-2d lotka-step (list 10 5) 0.1 600))

(define (extract-component traj index)
  (let loop ((i 0) (remaining traj))
    (if (null? remaining)
        '()
        (cons (list i (list-ref (car remaining) index))
              (loop (+ i 1) (cdr remaining))))))

(define prey-series (extract-component traj 0))
(define pred-series (extract-component traj 1))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/with
    (plot/line prey-series)
    (plot/line pred-series)))
```

[VISUAL: Two oscillating curves, prey and predator, out of phase. Prey peak precedes predator peak.]

