## §4. The Lorenz System and Strange Attractors

In 1963, meteorologist Edward Lorenz studied a simplified model of atmospheric convection:

```
dx/dt = σ(y - x)
dy/dt = x(ρ - z) - y
dz/dt = xy - βz
```

He used `σ=10, β=8/3, ρ=28`. The system is **three-dimensional** and **chaotic**: trajectories never repeat, never settle, but stay bounded — they trace a beautiful **strange attractor** shaped like a butterfly.

We'll approximate it with Euler's method.

```scheme
(define (lorenz-step x y z dt)
  (let ((sigma 10) (beta (/ 8 3)) (rho 28))
    (let ((dx (* sigma (- y x)))
          (dy (- (* x (- rho z)) y))
          (dz (- (* x y) (* beta z))))
      (list (+ x (* dx dt))
            (+ y (* dy dt))
            (+ z (* dz dt))))))

(define (orbit-3d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (apply step (append state0 (list dt)))))
        (cons state0 (orbit-3d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define traj (orbit-3d lorenz-step (list 1 1 1) 0.01 3000))

;; Extract (x, z) projection for plotting
(define (project-xz traj)
  (map (lambda (state) (list (car state) (caddr state))) traj))

(define xz-proj (project-xz traj))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/line xz-proj))
```

[VISUAL: A butterfly-shaped curve in the (x, z) plane — two lobes, the trajectory spiraling around one, then jumping to the other unpredictably.]

<!-- BUILD: run; Lorenz attractor projection -->

The orbit **never repeats**. It spirals around one lobe, then suddenly switches to the other. This is **deterministic chaos** in three dimensions.

---

### The Lorenz Attractor in 3D (Conceptual)

A true 3D plot would show the trajectory weaving through `(x, y, z)` space, tracing the butterfly's wings. Our 2D projection flattens it, but the structure is clear: a strange attractor — fractal, never self-intersecting, infinitely detailed.

[VISUAL: Ideally a 3D interactive; for now, multiple 2D projections (xy, xz, yz) side by side.]

<!-- BUILD: needs 3D scatter or multiple projection plots -->

The Lorenz system is why long-term weather forecasting is fundamentally limited. Tiny measurement errors grow exponentially.

---

### Sensitive Dependence in Lorenz

Start two orbits very close and watch them diverge.

```scheme
(define (lorenz-step x y z dt)
  (let ((sigma 10) (beta (/ 8 3)) (rho 28))
    (let ((dx (* sigma (- y x)))
          (dy (- (* x (- rho z)) y))
          (dz (- (* x y) (* beta z))))
      (list (+ x (* dx dt))
            (+ y (* dy dt))
            (+ z (* dz dt))))))

(define (orbit-3d step state0 dt n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      '()
      (let ((next (apply step (append state0 (list dt)))))
        (cons state0 (orbit-3d step next dt (- n 1))))))

(define traj1 (orbit-3d lorenz-step (list 1 1 1) 0.01 1500))
(define traj2 (orbit-3d lorenz-step (list 1.001 1 1) 0.01 1500))

(define (distance-3d s1 s2)
  (sqrt (+ (expt (- (car s1) (car s2)) 2)
           (expt (- (cadr s1) (cadr s2)) 2)
           (expt (- (caddr s1) (caddr s2)) 2))))

(define (pairwise-distance t1 t2)
  (if (or (null? t1) (null? t2))
      '()
      (cons (distance-3d (car t1) (car t2))
            (pairwise-distance (cdr t1) (cdr t2)))))

(define dists (pairwise-distance traj1 traj2))

(define (index-list lst)
  (let loop ((i 0) (remaining lst))
    (if (null? remaining)
        '()
        (cons (list i (car remaining))
              (loop (+ i 1) (cdr remaining))))))

(define dist-series (index-list dists))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/line dist-series))
```

[VISUAL: Distance between the two orbits grows exponentially at first, then saturates (bounded by the attractor's size).]

<!-- BUILD: run; exponential divergence then saturation -->

The initial exponential separation is the signature of chaos.

