## §5. Fractals from Iteration

A **fractal** is a geometric object with structure at every scale — zoom in, and you see the same complexity. Many fractals arise from **iterating a function in the complex plane**.

The **Mandelbrot set** is the most famous: for each complex number `c`, iterate `z → z² + c` starting from `z = 0`. If the orbit stays bounded, `c` is in the set. Otherwise it escapes to infinity.

We'll build a simplified fractal: iterating a real function and coloring points by how fast they escape.

---

### Escape-Time Coloring (Real Line)

Consider `f(x) = x² - 2`. Iterate from various starting points and count how many steps until `|x| > 10` (escape).

```scheme
(define (escape-time f x0 max-iter threshold)
  ;; Returns iteration count when |x| > threshold, or max-iter if bounded
  (let loop ((x x0) (n 0))
    (cond
      ((>= n max-iter) max-iter)
      ((> (abs x) threshold) n)
      (else (loop (f x) (+ n 1))))))

(define f-quadratic (lambda (x) (- (* x x) 2)))

;; Sample escape times for x in [-3, 3]
(define (sample-escape x-min x-max steps)
  (let ((dx (/ (- x-max x-min) steps)))
    (let loop ((i 0))
      (if (> i steps)
          '()
          (let ((x (+ x-min (* i dx))))
            (cons (list x (escape-time f-quadratic x 50 10))
                  (loop (+ i 1))))))))

(define samples (sample-escape -3 3 100))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/scatter samples))
```

[VISUAL: x-axis position, y-axis escape time. Some regions escape quickly, others take many iterations.]

<!-- BUILD: run; escape-time scatter -->

This is a 1D \"fractal\" profile. Points near the Julia set (the boundary between bounded and unbounded orbits) have complex escape behavior.

---

### The Logistic Map as a Fractal

The bifurcation diagram itself is a fractal: zoom into any region and you see self-similar structure. The cascade of period doublings repeats at finer scales, governed by **Feigenbaum's constant** `δ ≈ 4.669`.

[VISUAL: A zoomed region of the bifurcation diagram, showing smaller copies of the same tree structure.]

<!-- BUILD: conceptual; if we re-render a narrow r-range we'd see self-similarity -->

This universality — the same ratio governing period-doubling in vastly different systems — is one of chaos theory's deepest results.

---

### The Cantor Set (A Simple Fractal)

The **Cantor set** is built by repeatedly removing the middle third of intervals.

Start with `[0, 1]`. Remove `(1/3, 2/3)`, leaving `[0, 1/3] ∪ [2/3, 1]`. Remove the middle third of each remaining interval, and so on.

```scheme
(define (cantor-step intervals)
  ;; Each interval is (a b). Return list with middle thirds removed.
  (if (null? intervals)
      '()
      (let ((interval (car intervals)))
        (let ((a (car interval))
              (b (cadr interval)))
          (let ((third (/ (- b a) 3)))
            (append (list (list a (+ a third))
                          (list (+ a (* 2 third)) b))
                    (cantor-step (cdr intervals))))))))

(define gen0 (list (list 0 1)))
(define gen1 (cantor-step gen0))
(define gen2 (cantor-step gen1))
(define gen3 (cantor-step gen2))

gen3
```

[VISUAL: A list of 8 intervals: ((0 0.111...) (0.222... 0.333...) (0.666... 0.777...) (0.888... 1) and others)]

<!-- BUILD: run; print the intervals -->

After infinite iterations, the Cantor set has **measure zero** but **uncountably many points** — a fractal dust.

---

### Plotting the Cantor Set

We can draw the intervals as horizontal segments at different vertical levels (one level per generation).

```scheme
(define (cantor-step intervals)
  (if (null? intervals)
      '()
      (let ((interval (car intervals)))
        (let ((a (car interval))
              (b (cadr interval)))
          (let ((third (/ (- b a) 3)))
            (append (list (list a (+ a third))
                          (list (+ a (* 2 third)) b))
                    (cantor-step (cdr intervals))))))))

(define (cantor-generations n)
  (let loop ((gen (list (list 0 1))) (i 0))
    (if (>= i n)
        '()
        (cons gen (loop (cantor-step gen) (+ i 1))))))

(define gens (cantor-generations 5))

;; Flatten intervals with vertical offset
(define (flatten-with-y gens)
  (let loop ((remaining gens) (y 0))
    (if (null? remaining)
        '()
        (let ((gen (car remaining)))
          (append (map (lambda (interval)
                         (list (list (car interval) y)
                               (list (cadr interval) y)))
                       gen)
                  (loop (cdr remaining) (+ y 1)))))))

(define segments (flatten-with-y gens))

;; Plot each segment as a short line
(define (plot-segments segs)
  (if (null? segs)
      '()
      (cons (plot/line (car segs))
            (plot-segments (cdr segs)))))

(plot/render-svg
  (apply plot/with (plot-segments segments)))
```

[VISUAL: Horizontal bars at y=0,1,2,3,4, each level splitting the previous into smaller segments. Classic Cantor set visualization.]

<!-- BUILD: run; Cantor set fractal -->

Self-similarity is evident: each level is a scaled copy of the previous structure.

---

### The Koch Snowflake (Conceptual)

Another classic fractal: start with an equilateral triangle, replace each edge with a \"bump\" (four segments forming a smaller triangle), and repeat. The perimeter grows without bound, but the area stays finite.

[VISUAL: Ideally a geometric construction; for now, describe the iteration process.]

