### Iterating Complex Numbers (Conceptual Preview)

The Mandelbrot and Julia sets iterate `z → z² + c` in the complex plane. Each pixel `(x, y)` represents `c = x + iy`. We iterate, count escape time, and color accordingly.

With our `complex/` namespace, we could build this:

```scheme
;; Pseudocode (simplified)
(define (mandelbrot-pixel cx cy max-iter)
  (let loop ((z (complex/make 0 0)) (n 0))
    (if (>= n max-iter)
        max-iter
        (if (> (complex/modulus z) 2)
            n
            (loop (complex/+ (complex/pow z 2)
                             (complex/make cx cy))
                  (+ n 1))))))
```

Plotting the escape time for each pixel produces the iconic Mandelbrot set.

[VISUAL: A grid of pixels colored by escape time; the set is black (bounded), surrounded by colored bands (escape speed).]

<!-- BUILD: full implementation would sample a grid of complex points and render a heatmap; feasible but large -->

We'll leave the full Mandelbrot renderer as an advanced exercise. The principle is the same: iteration in the complex plane, escape-time coloring.

